==English==
===Etymology===
Persian {{ARchar|[[مهماندار]]}}, from {{ARchar|[[مهمان]]}} ''mihmān'' ‘guest’.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'meɪməndɑ:/

===Noun===
'''mehmandar'''
# an official [[courier]] appointed to [[escort]] an important traveller in Persian-speaking countires and the Indian subcontinent
#:*'''1974''': His '''mehmandar''' stood by, fresh as a clover from their walk, his arms crossed on his Aiantian chest. — Guy Davenport, ''Tatlin!''